Imports :

Imports cover the most common libraries.

  • NumPy is used for arrays and matrices.
  • cv2 is used for image manipulation.
  • matplotlib is used for plotting.
  • os is used for file and directory operations.
  • pickle is used for saving and loading python objects, essentially the loss stats.

Utils :

1# This function helps to load data from it's directory, 
2# resizes it into a 256x256 image and returns it as a numpy array
3def load_data(data_path):
4    images = []
5    filenames = os.listdir(data_path)
6    for file in filenames:
7        img = cv2.imread(data_path + file)
8        img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
9        img = cv2.resize(img, (256, 256))
10        images.append(img)
11    return np.array(images)
12
13# This function is used to sample random data from the dataset
14# normalize it and return it as a numpy couple array source, target
15def sample_date(batch_size, src, tar):
16    idx = np.random.randint(0, src.shape[0], batch_size)
17    s, t = norm_img(src[idx]), norm_img(tar[idx])
18    return s, t
19
20# This function helps during the training of the model to keep track about the latest prediction
21# it is known that with GANs there is no main metric to evaluate the model, so we use the loss
22# the loss gives us some idea about how good is the model doing, for example if there is a fast drop to 0
23# on the generator loss, it could annouce a mode collapse and the model is not working properly
24# so the one solution, is to evaluate the periodically the model by seeing the results with human eyes
25def show_sample(batch, x, y):
26    plt.figure(figsize=(6,6))
27    indx = np.random.choice(batch.shape[0], x * y, replace=False)
28    for i in range(0, x * y):
29        plt.subplot(x, y, i + 1)
30        image = batch[indx[i]]
31        fig = plt.imshow(image)
32        plt.axis('off')
33    plt.show()
34
35# Normalizing the images to -1 to 1, in order to use a tanh as output
36# speeds up a little bit the training and is better than using sigmoid
37def norm_img(img):
38    img = (img / 127.5) - 1
39    return img.astype('float32')
40
41# denormalizing the images to 0 to 255, in order to see the results
42def denorm_img(img):
43    img = (img + 1) * 127.5
44    return img.astype('uint8')

Pix2Pix Model :

1class Pix2Pix():
2    def __init__(self, discrminator_path=None, generator_path=None):
3        # useful constants
4        self.data_shape = img_shape
5        
6        # if given as input the model will be loaded from the given path
7        # this helps us to keep training the model from the last checkpoint
8        if discrminator_path:
9            self.discriminator = load_model(discrminator_path)
10        else:    
11            self.discriminator = self.build_discriminator()
12
13        # compiling the discriminator with a binary crossentropy loss as mentionned in the report
14        # with the same optimizer and the same metrics
15        self.discriminator.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=Adam(0.0002, 0.5),
16                                  loss_weights=[0.5])
17        
18        # same as the discriminator
19        if generator_path:
20            self.generator = load_model(generator_path)
21        else:
22            self.generator = self.build_generator()
23
24        # at the begining the discriminator is not trained, so we use the generator as a fixed model
25        self.discriminator.trainable = False
26
27        # combined means generator, we set it to combined because the backprogragation 
28        # has to be done not only on the generator (U-net) but also on the discriminator
29        # so by combining them we we backward the disc loss to the generator
30        combined_input = Input(shape=self.data_shape)
31        gen_output = self.generator(combined_input)
32        dis_output = self.discriminator([combined_input, gen_output])
33        self.combined = Model(combined_input, [dis_output, gen_output])
34        
35        # compiling the combined model with a binary crossentropy loss as mentionned in the report
36        # (which is the one for the discriminator of course, it's mentionned twice because the discriminator
37        # training alone is not same as the combined model training)
38        # MAE loss for the generator, i mention that it is also possible to use a MSE which sometimes can be better
39        # depending on the treated problem. MAE gives us smoother results, i guess it's better for segmentation
40        # but this is clearly not that much important since the data are mostly sparse binary images.
41        self.combined.compile(loss=['binary_crossentropy', 'mae'], optimizer=Adam(0.0002, 0.5),
42                            loss_weights=[1, 100])
43        
44    
45    def build_discriminator(self):
46        # Using a normal distribution to initialize the weights (always more stable)
47        init = RandomNormal(stddev=0.02)
48
49        # defining inputs
50        src_disc_input = Input(shape=self.data_shape)
51        target_disc_input = Input(shape=self.data_shape)
52        
53        # merging inputs (Fake image input and real image input)
54        merged = Concatenate()([src_disc_input, target_disc_input])
55        
56        # Never use a batch normalization at the first layer, it's not working properly
57        X = Conv2D(64, (4, 4), strides=(2, 2), padding='same', kernel_initializer=init)(merged)
58        X = LeakyReLU(alpha=0.2)(X)
59        
60        # default conv layer: Conv2D followed by a batchNorm followed by a LeakyRelu activation
61        X = Conv2D(128, (4, 4), strides=(2, 2), padding='same', kernel_initializer=init)(X)
62        X = BatchNormalization()(X)
63        X = LeakyReLU(alpha=0.2)(X)
64    
65        X = Conv2D(256, (4, 4), strides=(2, 2), padding='same', kernel_initializer=init)(X)
66        X = BatchNormalization()(X)
67        X = LeakyReLU(alpha=0.2)(X)
68
69        X = Conv2D(512, (4, 4), strides=(2, 2), padding='same', kernel_initializer=init)(X)
70        X = BatchNormalization()(X)
71        X = LeakyReLU(alpha=0.2)(X)
72
73        X = Conv2D(512, (4, 4), padding='same', kernel_initializer=init)(X)
74        X = BatchNormalization()(X)
75        X = LeakyReLU(alpha=0.2)(X)
76        
77        # same at the ending, never use a batch normalization at the last layer
78        X = Conv2D(1, (4, 4), padding='same', kernel_initializer=init)(X)
79        X = Activation('sigmoid')(X)
80        
81        discriminator = Model([src_disc_input, target_disc_input], X, name='discriminator')
82        return discriminator
83    
84    # Function used for building the generator (U net)
85    # We set the batchNorm as a parameter because it's important to not set it on input layer
86    # and also never use it with Dropout because it mistakes the normalization (since dropout disables
87    # neurons randomly, the batchNorm will count all the neurons on it's formulas, which is not what we want)
88    def downsample_block(self, link, filters, norm=True):
89        # Downsampling consists of a normal convolution and a batch normalization then a LeakyRelu
90        X = Conv2D(filters, (4, 4), (2, 2), padding='same', kernel_initializer=RandomNormal(stddev=0.02),
91                  use_bias=(not norm))(link)
92        if norm:
93            X = BatchNormalization()(X)
94        X = LeakyReLU(0.2)(X)
95        return X
96    
97    # Upsampling block is the same as the downsampling block but with a transposed convolution
98    # same problem for the batch normalization and dropout conflicts
99    # an better parameter here was to set kernel to 5x5 instead of 4x4 in order to avoid fragments on outputs
100    # (mentionned on the report)
101    def upsample_block(self, link, skip, filters, drop=True, norm=False):
102        X = Conv2DTranspose(filters, (4, 4), (2, 2), padding='same', kernel_initializer=RandomNormal(0.02),
103                           use_bias=False)(link)
104        if norm:
105            X = BatchNormalization(momentum=0.9)(X)
106        if drop:
107            X = Dropout(0.5)(X)
108        X = Concatenate()([X, skip])
109        X = LeakyReLU(0.2)(X)
110        return X
111    
112
113    # Building the generator
114    def build_generator(self):
115        encoder_input = Input(shape=self.data_shape)
116        
117        # Encoder part, No batch normalization on the first layer
118        X1 = self.downsample_block(encoder_input, 64, norm=False)
119        X2 = self.downsample_block(X1, 128)
120        X3 = self.downsample_block(X2, 256)
121        X4 = self.downsample_block(X3, 512)
122        X5 = self.downsample_block(X4, 512)
123        X6 = self.downsample_block(X5, 512)
124        X7 = self.downsample_block(X6, 512)
125        
126        # Middle connection
127        X = Conv2D(512, (4, 4), strides=(2, 2), padding='same', kernel_initializer=RandomNormal(0.02))(X7)
128        X = Activation('relu')(X)
129        
130        # Decoder part
131        # No norm at the first layer, better use dropout on first layers and then normlizing on the after ones
132        # For the last layer, no dropout and no norm as explained above
133        X = self.upsample_block(X, X7, 512, drop=True, norm=False)
134        X = self.upsample_block(X, X6, 512, drop=True, norm=False)
135        X = self.upsample_block(X, X5, 512, drop=True, norm=False)
136        X = self.upsample_block(X, X4, 512, drop=False, norm=True)
137        X = self.upsample_block(X, X3, 256, drop=False, norm=True)
138        X = self.upsample_block(X, X2, 128, drop=False, norm=True)
139        X = self.upsample_block(X, X1, 64, drop=False, norm=False)
140        
141        X = Conv2DTranspose(3, (4, 4), (2, 2), padding='same', kernel_initializer=RandomNormal(0.02))(X)
142        X = Activation('tanh')(X)
143        
144        generator = Model(encoder_input, X, name='generator')
145        return generator
146    
147    # Training function
148    # parameters:
149    #   - epochs: number of epochs
150    #   - batch_size: size of the batch
151    #   - step: number of iterations for each epoch (set it to size of dataset for a true epoch value)
152    #   - save_at: number of epochs between each save
153    def train(self, epochs=50, step=100, batch_size=1, save_at=2):
154        # initialize some useful constants, like the output shape of the discriminator
155        d_output = self.discriminator.output_shape[1]
156        progbar = Progbar(step)
157
158        # we initiate some empty arrays for storing the losses
159        total_d_loss_real = []
160        total_d_loss_fake = []
161        total_g_loss = []
162        stats = []
163        
164        # for each epoch
165        for epoch in range(1, epochs + 1):
166            for i in range(step):
167                progbar.update(i + 1)
168                
169                # we take a sample of real data randomly (image, gt_mask)
170                real_s, real_t = sample_date(batch_size, src, tar)
171                # we generate outputs for the discriminator, outputs here are ones since those are real data
172                # it could be possible to add some normal noise to these outputs to make the training more stable
173                # for example, 0.97 instead of 1.0 ... etc
174                real_labels = np.ones((batch_size, d_output, d_output, 1))
175                
176                # we get fake data now, we generate it with the generator
177                # and assign zeros 
178                fake_s = self.generator.predict(real_s)
179                fake_labels = np.zeros((batch_size, d_output, d_output, 1))
180                
181                # we train the discriminator with the real data and the fake data
182                # DO NEVER train on mixed batches, always train on real first and then fake (or inversed)
183                d_loss_real = self.discriminator.train_on_batch([real_s, real_t], real_labels)
184                d_loss_fake = self.discriminator.train_on_batch([real_s, fake_s], fake_labels)
185
186                # we train the generator then (combined model) by giving it real input images and masks
187                # real_t doesn't matter here, we just want to train the generator
188                # note that backpropagation is done on the combined model, so it runs on the discriminator too
189                # and this is what makes the generator learn better the signal of data
190                g_loss, _, _ = self.combined.train_on_batch(real_s, [real_labels, real_t])
191                
192                # appending the losses
193                total_d_loss_fake.append(d_loss_fake)
194                total_d_loss_real.append(d_loss_real)
195                total_g_loss.append(g_loss)
196                
197                stats.append((d_loss_fake, d_loss_real, g_loss))
198                
199            # print the losses for the current epoch
200            print('Epoch %d : Real discriminator loss : %f --- Fake discriminator loss : %f --- Generator loss : %f'
201                 % (epoch, np.mean(total_d_loss_real), np.mean(total_d_loss_fake), np.mean(total_g_loss)))
202            test_sample = denorm_img(self.generator.predict(real_s))
203
204            # show the test sample
205            show_sample(test_sample, 1, 1)
206            total_d_loss_fake.clear()
207            total_d_loss_real.clear()
208            total_g_loss.clear()
209            
210            # saving the model every save_at epochs
211            if epoch % 10 == 0:
212                self.discriminator.save('discriminator_model')
213                self.generator.save('generator_model')
214                print('models saved')
215                with open('stats {}.pickle'.format(epoch), 'wb') as f:
216                    pickle.dump(stats, f)
217                print('stats saved')
218    
219    # function to display actual architecture of the model
220    def summary(self):
221        self.discriminator.summary()
222        self.generator.summary()
223        self.combined.summary()
224
